{"cursor":"4413","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Greek Dimos |name = Samarina |name_local = Î£Î±Î¼Î±ÏÎ¯Î½Î± |image_map =\nKoinotita Samarinas.png |map_caption = Location within the regional unit |periph\n= West Macedonia |periphunit = Grevena |municipality = Grevena |pop_municunit =\n378 |population_as_of = 2011 |area = |elevation = |lat_deg = 40 |lat_min = 6\n|lon_deg = 21 |lon_min = 4 |postal_code = 511 00 |area_code = 24620 |licence =\n|mayor = |website = |image_skyline = |caption_skyline = |city_flag = |city_seal\n= |districts = |party = |since = |elevation_min = 1380 |elevation_max = 1500 }}\n\n'Samarina' (, ) is a village and a former municipality in Grevena regional unit,\nWest Macedonia, Greece. Since the 2011 local government reform it is part of the\nmunicipality Grevena, of which it is a municipal unit. [ht-\ntp://www.kedke.gr/uploads2010/FEKB129211082010_kallikratis.pdf Kallikratis law]\nGreece Ministry of Interior  Its population primarily consists of\nAromanians (sometimes called Vlachs). It attracts many tourists due to its\nscenic location and beautiful pine and beech forests. The population was 378\npeople as of 2011.\n\nSamarina is the most famous of all the Aromanian villages of the Pindus and the\ninhabitants are fiercely proud of their heritage and traditions. Every summer on\nAugust 15, on the feast of the Dormition of the Virgin, Samarinans from all over\nthe world assemble on their ancestral village to celebrate. There, on the main\nsquare outside the Great Church, they perform the \"Great Dance\" (Greek: TranÃ³s\nChorÃ³s, Aromanian: Corlu Mari): thousands of people hold hands and form\nconcentric circles, and they walk slowly and ceremonially counterclockwise,\nwhile singing their traditional songs in a rousing unison chorus.\n","linknr":167,"url":"Samarina","recorded":1375058565,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Samarina&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Samarina&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.i